// C3: Physical sensing components
instance InsideTemperatureSensor1 : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "DS18S20 digital temperature sensor mounted inside the insulated styrofoam box, communicating over 1‑Wire via Raspberry Pi GPIO."
    DTDFVocab:producedData TemperatureDataTransmitted
]

instance InsideTemperatureSensor2 : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "DS18S20 digital temperature sensor mounted inside the insulated styrofoam box, communicating over 1‑Wire via Raspberry Pi GPIO."
    DTDFVocab:producedData TemperatureDataTransmitted
]

instance OutsideTemperatureSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "DS18S20 digital temperature sensor attached externally to monitor ambient conditions, communicating over 1‑Wire via Raspberry Pi GPIO."
    DTDFVocab:producedData TemperatureDataTransmitted
]

// C4: Physical-to-virtual interaction
instance TemperatureDataTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom InsideTemperatureSensor1, InsideTemperatureSensor2, OutsideTemperatureSensor
]

// C10: Models/Data
instance TwoParameterThermalModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Coupled differential equations model with two free parameters: overall heat‑transfer coefficient and effective thermal capacitance of the system."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo PythonCalibrationSimulationTool
]

instance FourParameterThermalModel : DTDFVocab:Model [
    base:desc "Extended thermal model with four free parameters, adding heatbed inertia and fan dynamic response to capture system behavior more accurately."
    DTDFVocab:inputTo PythonCalibrationSimulationTool
]

// C10: Data
instance TemperatureReadingData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Timestamped temperature readings from two interior DS18S20 sensors and one exterior sensor, received via RabbitMQ."
    DTDFVocab:fromData TemperatureDataTransmitted
    DTDFVocab:inputTo RaspberryPiController, PythonCalibrationSimulationTool, ActuationService
]

// C11: Enablers
instance RaspberryPiController : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Raspberry Pi 4 Model B running Raspbian, executing Python 3 scripts that interface with DS18S20 sensors via 1‑Wire and I²C and control heatbed/fan via GPIO."
    DTDFVocab:enables ActuationService
]

instance RabbitMQBroker : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "RabbitMQ AMQP broker mediating telemetry and command exchange between the Pi firmware and DT backend."
    DTDFVocab:enables CommunicationService
]

instance PythonCalibrationSimulationTool : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Python process DT backend that subscribes to RabbitMQ telemetry, runs calibration (SciPy least‑squares), runs simulation, and exposes Flask web server for visualization."
    DTDFVocab:enables CalibrationService, SimulationService, PredictionService, VisualizationService
]

instance FlaskVisualizationServer : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Flask web server exposing real‑time sensor data, model state, and predictions."
    DTDFVocab:enables VisualizationService
]

// C6: Services
instance MonitoringService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Real‑time ingestion of temperature data from DS18S20 sensors via Raspberry Pi, published on RabbitMQ for downstream consumers and stored for trend analysis."
    DTDFVocab:provides TemperatureTrendInsight
]

instance ActuationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Bang‑bang controller that toggles the heatbed element and fan via GPIO to maintain target temperature envelope."
    DTDFVocab:provides VerifyActuatorStatusAction
]

instance CommunicationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Handles RabbitMQ communication between physical twin and digital twin backend."
]

instance CalibrationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Auto‑calibrates model parameters using live telemetry and SciPy optimization."
    DTDFVocab:provides CalibrationStatusInsight
]

instance SimulationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Runs two thermal simulation models (2‑parameter and 4‑parameter) to predict internal temperature response to heater power and ambient conditions."
    DTDFVocab:provides ModelValidationInsight
]

instance PredictionService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Forecasts short‑term temperature trajectories to enable pre‑emptive adjustment."
    DTDFVocab:provides TemperaturePredictionInsight
]

instance SupervisoryControlService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Outputs safety alerts and recommends power setpoints based on model predictions and anomaly detection."
    DTDFVocab:provides SafetyAlertInsight, AdjustPowerSetpointAction
]

instance VisualizationService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Interactive web dashboard that displays real‑time sensor data, model state, and prediction traces."
    DTDFVocab:provides DashboardInsight
]

// C17: Insights
instance TemperatureTrendInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Real‑time temperature trends aggregated from internal and external sensors for monitoring purposes."
]

instance ModelValidationInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Comparison of simulation predictions against actual sensor measurements to evaluate model accuracy."
]

instance CalibrationStatusInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Status report of model parameter calibration, including fit quality and confidence."
]

instance TemperaturePredictionInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Short‑term temperature forecast derived from calibrated thermal models."
]

instance SafetyAlertInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Alert triggered when temperature deviations exceed predefined safety thresholds."
]

instance DashboardInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Comprehensive visual representation of sensor data, model predictions, and supervisory recommendations."
]

// C17: Actions
instance AdjustPowerSetpointAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Recommendation to adjust heatbed power setpoint to maintain target temperature."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic true
]

instance VerifyActuatorStatusAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Manual verification action to confirm heatbed and fan are within safe operational limits."
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic false
]

instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Control commands, issued by the DT’s controller logic, are sent over RabbitMQ to the low‑level driver. The controller, which implements a bang‑bang strategy, receives temperature feedback, decides on fan and heatbed states, and instructs the driver to actuate the respective hardware. Confirmation is implicitly handled by the driver’s safe protocol when publishing the actuator states back to RabbitMQ."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "Sensor data from the incubator’s temperature sensors is read by the Raspberry Pi controller and fed into the digital twin. The twin performs model calibration and Kalman‑filter state estimation within the loop defined by the controller’s driver messages. The documents do not specify any explicit synchronization frequency, latency requirement, or temporal granularity for these processes."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The digital twin orchestrates sensor data collection, online calibration of the parameterised thermal model (Model B), a Kalman‑filter based estimation of the heat‑bed temperature, anomaly detection via filter innovations, and what‑if co‑simulation runs that evaluate and optimise controller parameters. All modules run on the Raspberry Pi host; sensor readings and low‑level driver messages are transmitted through a local messaging bus, allowing the twin to update models and adjust control logic in real time."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "Modeling, calibration, real‑time data integration, monitoring, optimisation and supervisory control. During the development phase the digital twin is constructed as a set of numerical simulation models (two versions described in the paper), accompanied by a calibration algorithm that continuously updates model parameters based on sensor data. In runtime the data stream from the physical twin (two internal and one external temperature sensor) feeds the monitoring component, which checks safety and performance constraints; when violations are detected a supervisory controller or human operator can modify the physical twin or the model. This flow represents the typical lifecycle phases: design, calibration, validation, deployment, monitoring, and evolution."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is assessed by comparing simulated temperature trajectories (from both two‑parameter and four‑parameter thermal models) against experimentally recorded temperature data during calibration runs. The four‑parameter model is deemed superior due to its better representation of the heatbed’s thermal inertia, making it the preferred model for ongoing DT development. Validation procedures involve periodic injection of test temperature profiles and measurement of prediction error; however, explicit uncertainty quantification sources, error correction mechanisms, or formal quality assurance processes are not detailed in the documents."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The DT and PT interact over a RabbitMQ broker that implements the AMQP protocol over TCP. The networking topology is a star configuration with the Raspberry Pi controller as a client and the RabbitMQ server as a central message broker (local to the incubator enclosure). Communication occurs over the local network (Wi‑Fi or Ethernet). While RabbitMQ supports high availability and clustering, the documentation indicates that the broker can be deployed on‑premises (e.g., on the Raspberry Pi) or in the cloud; however, no explicit redundancy or load‑balancing configuration is described in the case study. The batch size and latency are not quantified, but the control loop requires sub‑second latency to maintain temperature stability."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The DT’s core components—controller, low‑level driver, and simulation models—are deployed on a Raspberry Pi 4 Model B, serving as an edge device that runs on‑premises. The RabbitMQ message broker is also instantiated locally on the same Pi (or on a local network) according to the repository’s deployment scripts. Computational resources are modest (single‑core CPU, 2 GB RAM) and storage is sufficient to host the software stack and log files. The system is designed for small‑scale deployment; scalability mechanisms (horizontal scaling, clustering) or high‑availability redundancy are not included in the documented setup."
]

instance horizontal_integration : DTDFVocab:HoriIntegration [
    base:desc "The Twin interfaces with the physical incubator through the Raspberry Pi’s GPIO pins (for connecting sensors, fan, and heatbed controls).  Software data exchange within the Twin relies on the local RabbitMQ broker; no external communication protocols or enterprise interoperability standards (such as OPC‑UA, MQTT, REST) are documented.  Consequently, the Twin’s horizontal integration scope is limited to the immediate physical plant and its internal, locally‑hosted components."
]